caption.text:
As an objective cosmic reality, time literally does not exist. There is no beginning and there is no end. You and I are in a mere state of being. 
One hundred years from now, it is highly likely we will be forgotten. It may come across as a cynical thought, but truth be told. Defeatist Somewhat, but I personally find it to be a refreshing thought. I endure a feeling of awe, much like when gazing at the Steirvern night sky, to be part of something, so incredibly huge. 
As saddening as the thought of our lives and everything we know seizing to exist may be, the same atoms which make us, dispersed everywhere will not mean we are gone. In a million years from now, we may be a part of a newly born star shinning down on new worlds. We will forever be everywhere, but most importantly, forever be a part of something.

A certain fact remains. Our lives are part of a poetic universe, and however insignificant we may seem in comparison to the world, to feel soulful when looking up at the vast amount of planets and stars, to know that not one is looking back, able to feel the way we can when experiencing that moment,  demonstrates an overwhelming significance that scale can never touch upon. - @saiif

Surely something's wrong if it's considered the social norm for our lives to revolve around mindless technology, and actually be comfortable with it. Even as i talk about it, you're probably thinking, "lol yeah whatever". The places I've shared with you exist, and you don't feel the need to witness it for yourself? It seems more and more true that the common man is but a slave to the system. #ApathyPrevails üòî

As an objective cosmic reality, time literally does not exist. There is no beginning and there is no end, you and I are in a mere state of being. 
One hundred years from now, it is highly likely we will be forgotten. A cynacal thought, but truth be told. Defeatist? Somewhat, but other than being used amusingly to stir up conviction in the optimistic, I personally find it to be a refreshing thought. I endure a feeling of awe, much like when gazing at the vastness of this Steirvern sky, to be part of something, so incomprehensibly huge.  As saddening as the thought of our lives and everything we know seizing to exist may be, the same atoms which make us, dispersed everywhere will not mean we are gone, in a million years from now, we may be a part of a newly born star shinning down on new worlds much like ours. 
We will forever be everywhere, but most importantly, forever be a part of something. 
A certain fact remains. Our lives are a part of a beautiful poetic universe, and however insignificant we may seem in comparison to the world, all it takes is to look up. Feeling soulful when witnessing such beauty and to know nothing is looking back, able to feel the way which we can, demonstrates an overwhelming significance that scale and time can never touch upon. - @saiif
